Raul Polit Casillas leads the Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) team at a NASA branch in Pasadena, California that's developing a metal fabric strongly resembling chainmail in both look and functionality. On the smooth, tiled side, the metallic fabric reflects light, while the other side absorbs it, giving it two forms of functionality right off the bat. It can also be printed and designed both on earth and in a spaceship, and since it's printed, you can make slight design changes and print it out in one fluid motion rather than undergoing the painstaking process of linking each piece by hand. Mark Bradford on this month’s cover of Art Review, May 2017. ‘’I’m not good at describing the real. I’m good at pointing to it in an emotional way or an intense way.’ The real, in Bradford’s work, is nevertheless fully present; the posters and endpapers are, in a sense, the very fabric of the city, fragments from its economic margins through which other more ephemeral or subjective realities are triangulated.’
–
In the feature ‘Mark Bradford: That’s not gonna happen’ Jonathan Griffin explores the artist’s refusal to be an object, the vulnerablity of the margin and representing America after Trump.
